Done. Fresh-eyes notes are appended at the bottom of `src/blog/people/drafts/julia-fox.md`.

**Reviewed:** the Julia Fox draft (Enneagram Type 4). It's a strong, cohesive piece — the object/author thesis is distinct from your other Type 4 drafts, the Kanye empathy turn is the best paragraph, and the critic pressure is handled well.

**The two biggest issues I flagged:**

1. **Gianna is missing.** Fox's best friend Gianna Valdes died of an overdose in 2019 — she was with Fox when she got cast in *Uncut Gems*, and by every account of the memoir it was that death, *not* motherhood, that drove Fox to get sober (she even consulted a medium to reach her). The draft credits the whole growth turn to "Motherhood pulled the other direction." A reader who knows the memoir will feel the hole immediately, and it's a missed payoff: the wound isn't just that people leave her, it's that she keeps *losing* them — grief is the one thing she couldn't sign and sell.

2. **Fashion is under-weighted as her actual medium.** The thesis is "she's the one holding the brush," and her most literal ongoing proof is that she builds the images people photograph — DIY outfits from beach towels, fallen leaves, condoms, upcycled denim. The draft only touches fashion once, as a Halloween costume.

Smaller notes in the block cover the "sign" verb becoming a tic and the gaze/"looking" payoff tripling up at the close. No body edits made, per the command.

Sources for the reality check: [Bustle on *Down the Drain* / Gianna](https://www.bustle.com/entertainment/julia-fox-down-the-drain-memoir-friendship-addiction-interview), [Bustle on the medium detail](https://www.bustle.com/entertainment/julia-fox-down-the-drain-medium-contact-dead-friend), [Grazia on her DIY fashion](https://graziamagazine.com/me/articles/julia-foxs-diy-fashion/).
